SIMPLE: ferry
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ferry
<hw>Fer"ry</hw> <pr>(f⟦ecr⟧r"r⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Ferried</conjf>
<pr>(-r⟦icr⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Ferrying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>ferien</ets> to
convey, AS. <ets>ferian</ets>, from <ets>faran</ets> to go; akin to
Icel. <ets>ferja</ets> to ferry, Goth. <ets>farjan</ets> to sail. See
<er>Fare</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To carry or transport over a
river, strait, or other narrow water, in a boat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To convey back and forth regularly between two
points in a vehicle; <as>as, part of her day was spent <ex>ferrying</ex>
the kids to and from school</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ferry</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ferry
<hw>Fer"ry</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To pass over water in a boat or
by a ferry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>ferry</qex> over this Lethean sound⟦br⟧
Both to and fro.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ferry</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Ferry
<hw>Fer"ry</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Ferries</plw>
<pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>feri</ets>; akin to Icel.
<ets>ferja</ets>, Sw. <ets>f⟦aum⟧rja</ets>, Dan. <ets>f⟦ae⟧rge</ets>, G.
<ets>f⟦aum⟧hre</ets>. See <er>Ferry</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A place where persons or things are carried across a
river, arm of the sea, etc., in a ferryboat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It can pass the <qex>ferry</qex> backward into light.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To row me o'er the <qex>ferry</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Campbell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A vessel in which passengers and goods are conveyed
over narrow waters; a ferryboat; a wherry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A franchise or right to maintain a vessel for
carrying passengers and freight across a river, bay, etc., charging
tolls.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Ferry bridge</b></col>, <cd>a ferryboat adapted in its
structure for the transfer of railroad trains across a river or
bay.</cd> -- <col><b>Ferry railway</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Railway</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ferryboat</ent>⟦br⟧
